04538nam a2200613Ia 9780674020672DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20092002mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740206727 a10.4159/97806740206722doi  a(DE-B1597)574303  a(OCoLC)1257323980  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aQH429.2.B38 ǂb A3 2002eb 7aBIO0150002bisacsh04a576.50921 aBeckwith, Jon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaking Genes, Making Waves :bA Social Activist in Science /cJon Beckwith. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2009] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (252 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1 The Quail Farmer and the Scientist -- t2 Becoming a Scientist -- t3 Becoming an Activist -- t4 On Which Side Are the Angels? -- t5 The Tarantella of the Living -- t6 Does Science Take a Back Seat to Politics? -- t7 Their Own Atomic History -- t8 The Myth of the Criminal Chromosome -- t9 It’s the Devil in Your DNA -- t10 I’m Not Very Scary Anymore -- t11 Story-Telling in Science -- t12 Geneticists and the Two Cultures -- t13 The Scientist and the Quail Farmer -- tBibliography -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1969, Jon Beckwith and his colleagues succeeded in isolating a gene from the chromosome of a living organism. Announcing this startling achievement at a press conference, Beckwith took the opportunity to issue a public warning about the dangers of genetic engineering. Jon Beckwith's book, the story of a scientific life on the front line, traces one remarkable man's dual commitment to scientific research and social responsibility over the course of a career spanning most of the postwar history of genetics and molecular biology.A thoroughly engrossing memoir that recounts Beckwith's halting steps toward scientific triumphs--among them, the discovery of the genetic element that turns genes on--as well as his emergence as a world-class political activist, Making Genes, Making Waves is also a compelling history of the major controversies in genetics over the last thirty years. Presenting the science in easily understandable terms, Beckwith describes the dramatic changes that transformed biology between the late 1950s and our day, the growth of the radical science movement in the 1970s, and the personalities involved throughout. He brings to light the differing styles of scientists as well as the different ways in which science is presented within the scientific community and to the public at large. Ranging from the travails of Robert Oppenheimer and the atomic bomb to the Human Genome Project and recent "Science Wars," Beckwith's book provides a sweeping view of science and its social context in the latter half of the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Science & Technology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674020672?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674020672423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674020672/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles